04018nam a22005415i 9780804773447DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202009cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047734477 a10.1515/97808047734472doi  a(DE-B1597)564154  a(OCoLC)1198930994  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDS731.N39bS55 2010 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.895/4a305.89541 aShih, Chuan-kang, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQuest for Harmony :bThe Moso Traditions of Sexual Union and Family Life. /cChuan-kang Shih. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on the Usage of Kinship Terms in English -- tLegend of Symbols in Kinship Diagrams -- tIntroduction -- t1. The People and Their History -- t2. The Political Structure and Cultural Environment of Traditional Moso Society -- t3. Tisese: The Primary Pattern of Institutionalized Sexual Union -- t4. Marriage: The Secondary Pattern of Institutionalized Sexual Union -- t5. Matrilineal Descent and Matrilineal Ideology -- t6. The Moso Social Organization -- t7. Navigating through the Web of Social Relations -- t8. Household Life among the Moso -- t9. The Unusual Moso Gender System -- t10. Religions and Rituals among the Moso -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tCharacter List -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this long-awaited ethnography, Chuan-kang Shih details the traditional social and cultural conditions of the Moso, a matrilineal group living on the border of Yunnan and Sichuan Provinces in southwest China. Among the Moso, a majority of the adult population practice a visiting system called tisese instead of marriage as the normal sexual and reproductive institution. Until recently, tisese was noncontractual, nonobligatory, and nonexclusive. Partners lived and worked in separate households. The only prerequisite for a tisese relationship was a mutual agreement between the man and the woman to allow sexual access to each other. In a comprehensive account, Quest for Harmony explores this unique practice specifically, and offers thorough documentation, fine-grained analysis, and an engaging discussion of the people, history, and structure of Moso society. Drawing on the author's extensive fieldwork, conducted from 1987 to 2006, this is the first ethnography of the Moso written in English.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aMatrilineal kinshipzChina, Southwest. 0aNaxi (Chinese people)xKinship. 0aNaxi (Chinese people)xSexual behavior. 0aNaxi (Chinese people)xSocial life and customs. 0aSex rolezChina, Southwest. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804773447zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804773447423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804773447.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles